Modifiable Areal Unit Problem

# independent variable
ind <- c(87, 95, 72, 37, 44, 24,
         40, 55, 55, 38, 88, 34,
         41, 30, 26, 35, 38, 24,
         14, 56, 37, 34,  8, 18,
         49, 44, 51, 67, 17, 37,
         55, 25, 33, 32, 59, 54)

# dependent variable
dep <- c(72, 75, 85, 29, 58, 30,
         50, 60, 49, 46, 84, 23,
         21, 46, 22, 42, 45, 14,
         19, 36, 48, 23,  8, 29,
         38, 47, 52, 52, 22, 48,
         58, 40, 46, 38, 35, 55)
plot(ind, dep)
m <- glm(dep ~ ind)

# create regression formula
f <- paste0('y = ', round(s$coefficients[2], 4), 'x + ', round(s$coefficients[1], 4))
# add the text in variable f to the plot
text(0, 96, f, pos=4)
# compute r-squared
R2 <- cor(dep, predict(m))^2

# set up the expression (a bit complex, this)
r2 <- bquote(italic(R)^2 == .(round(R2, 4)))
# and add it to the plot
text(0, 85, r2, pos=4)

# compute regression line
# create a data.frame with the range (minimum and maximum) of values of ind
px <- data.frame(ind = range(ind))
# use the regression model to get predicted value for dep at these two extremes
py <- predict(m, px)
# combine the min and max values and the predicted values
ln <- cbind(px, py)
# add to the plot as a line
lines(ln, lwd=2)

Question 1: Create these matrices from ind and dep without using byrow=TRUE. Hint: use the t function after you made the matrix.

mi <- matrix(ind, ncol=6, nrow=6, byrow=TRUE)
md <- matrix(dep, ncol=6, nrow=6, byrow=TRUE)

mi2  <- matrix(ind, ncol=6, nrow=6)
md2 <- matrix(dep, ncol=6, nrow=6) 

#without using byrow=TRUE, default is byrow = false, so I transpose the matrices here
mi2 = t(mi2)
md2 = t(md2)

Question 2: Instead of the mean function What other functions could, in principle, reasonably be used in an aggregation of raster cells?

In principle, other functions to use instead of mean would be modal, min, max, and sum.

Weights matrix

#get weight matrix
W <- 1 / D
round(W, 4)
##        A      B      C      D      E      F
## A    Inf 0.0143 0.0144 0.0148 0.0345 0.0219
## B 0.0143    Inf 0.0185 0.0092 0.0101 0.0099
## C 0.0144 0.0185    Inf 0.0147 0.0112 0.0088
## D 0.0148 0.0092 0.0147    Inf 0.0163 0.0095
## E 0.0345 0.0101 0.0112 0.0163    Inf 0.0224
## F 0.0219 0.0099 0.0088 0.0095 0.0224    Inf
#Row-normalization is not that difficult either. First get rid if the Inf values by changing them to NA. (Where did the Inf values come from?)
W[!is.finite(W)] <- NA

#compute row sums
rtot <- rowSums(W, na.rm=TRUE) 
# this is equivalent to 
# rtot <- apply(W, 1, sum, na.rm=TRUE)
rtot
##          A          B          C          D          E          F 
## 0.09989170 0.06207541 0.06763182 0.06443810 0.09445017 0.07248377
W <- W / rtot
rowSums(W, na.rm=TRUE) #Divide the rows by their totals and check if they row sums add up to 1
## A B C D E F 
## 1 1 1 1 1 1

Question 6. The SpatialPolygonDataFrame class is defined in package sp. But we never used library(‘sp’) . So how is it possible that we have one of such objects?

When we loaded the raster package, it also loaded the sp package. The sp package is required for the functionality of the raster package.
